Here's a layered approach to diagnose HttpClient timeouts in a .NET 8 Windows service:

### 1. **Enable .NET Event Source Logging**
```csharp
// Add to your service startup
using System.Diagnostics.Tracing;

var listener = new ConsoleEventListener();
// Captures DNS, Socket, and HTTP events

[EventSource(Name = "Microsoft-System-Net-Http")]
sealed class ConsoleEventListener : EventListener
{
    protected override void OnEventSourceCreated(EventSource es)
    {
        if (es.Name.StartsWith("Microsoft-System-Net"))
            EnableEvents(es, EventLevel.LogAlways);
    }
}
```

### 2. **Network-Level Capture (best signal)**
```powershell
# ETW trace (lightweight, production-safe)
netsh trace start capture=yes tracefile=C:\diag\net.etl

# Reproduce the issue, then:
netsh trace stop

# Or use dotnet-trace for .NET-specific events:
dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --providers Microsoft-System-Net-Http,Microsoft-System-Net-Sockets,Microsoft-System-Net-NameResolution
```

### 3. **Check Common Root Causes**
```powershell
# Socket/port exhaustion (most common cause)
netstat -ano | findstr <PID> | measure
# If thousands of TIME_WAIT connections → you're not reusing HttpClient

# DNS resolution delays
Resolve-DnsName your-api.example.com | Format-Table -AutoSize
Measure-Command { Resolve-DnsName your-api.example.com }

# Firewall/proxy interference
Test-NetConnection -ComputerName your-api.example.com -Port 443 -InformationLevel Detailed
```

### 4. **Likely Fix: Use `IHttpClientFactory`**
The #1 cause of HttpClient timeouts in services is **socket exhaustion** from `new HttpClient()` per request. Use the factory pattern:

```csharp
// In DI registration
services.AddHttpClient("MyApi", c => {
    c.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
    c.Timeout = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(60);
});
```

### Quick Checklist
| Check | Command |
|---|---|
| Port exhaustion | `netstat -ano \| findstr <PID>` |
| DNS latency | `Measure-Command { Resolve-DnsName ... }` |
| TLS issues | `dotnet-trace` with `System.Net.Security` provider |
| Connectivity | `Test-NetConnection -Port 443` |

Start with `netstat` to check socket count — if you see hundreds/thousands of connections in `TIME_WAIT`, socket exhaustion is your answer and `IHttpClientFactory` is the fix.
